        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe\u2019s ten, the Outer Richmond fog thick outside his father\u2019s shop. His father lets him hold a half-finished suit jacket, the smell of steamed wool and chalk in the air. He traces the hand-stitching of the canvas lining. \u2018This is the soul, Marco. What you don\u2019t see makes all the difference.\u2019 It wasn't just a lesson in tailoring; it was an inheritance. This moment became the foundation of his belief that true value lies in unseen quality and honest craftsmanship, a principle that now guides every brand decision he makes.\n\n2.\nAt twelve, he\u2019d taken a nasty fall, his knee a bloody mess. His mother, just home from a 12-hour nursing shift, cleaned the wound with practiced efficiency. No coddling, just a firm hand and a quiet, \u201cYou are fine.\u201d He felt a flash of resentment, then a wave of deep respect for her strength. It was then he internalized her pragmatism. That quiet fortitude became the engine for his own ambition, the part of him that plans, executes, and endures long days in pursuit of a precise goal.\n\n3.\nIt was 2 AM during his summer marketing internship. The team was stuck rebranding a leather goods maker. Marco stared at a worn satchel, channeling his father. \u201cThis isn\u2019t a bag,\u201d he said suddenly, \u201cit\u2019s three generations of Saturday mornings at the Ferry Building.\u201d The room fell silent. He felt a jolt of pure clarity. At twenty-one, the epiphany struck: his gift wasn't in making the object, but in articulating its soul. That night, he started his journey to become a storyteller for beautiful things.\n\n4.\nAged twenty-five and just back from the East Coast, he walked through Hayes Valley. The neighborhood felt alien\u2014sleek, expensive, and humming with a frequency he barely recognized. He stood where a familiar corner store used to be, now a minimalist cafe. It was a potent cocktail of ambition and loss. This wasn't the city he left, and yet it was the one he had to conquer. That walk solidified his complicated love for SF, embedding in him a quiet drive to find his authentic place within its new identity.\n\n5.\nLast year, at a brand event at SFMOMA, he saw a renowned architect\u2014a man known for understated style\u2014wearing one of the watches he markets. There was no flash, just quiet appreciation. Marco saw his father\u2019s hands, then pictured his own future brand. In that instant, his abstract dream gained weight and form. It wasn't about luxury; it was about creating objects of permanent, personal value. That quiet observation at twenty-six sharpened his ambition, clarifying his path from brand manager to brand creator."
